\details{
\strong{Pairing on raw responses.} The synonym pairs are the item pairs whose
whole-sample inter-item correlation exceeds \code{critical_r} (default \code{0.60}).
Pairing uses the \strong{raw} responses, with no reverse-scoring: a reverse-keyed
item simply forms negative correlations and so is never paired as a synonym
(it may instead be an \emph{antonym}; see the companion antonyms index). The score
is the single correlation across all qualifying pairs' stacked values, matching
\code{careless::psychsyn(resample_na = FALSE)} to the bit.

\strong{No pairs found.} \code{critical_r} is a property of the \emph{inventory}, not the
respondent: on broad personality inventories the strongest inter-item
correlations can fall below \code{0.60}, so no synonym pairs qualify, every value is
\code{NA}, and the index abstains with a warning. Lower \code{critical_r} to surface
pairs, or compute the index on a more homogeneous scale.

\strong{Cutoff.} The default flags the lowest-consistency respondents: the cutoff is
the empirical \code{fpr} quantile of the observed scores (the 5th percentile by
default) and respondents at or below it are flagged. This is a \strong{ranking}
convention -- a sample percentile flags \code{fpr} of respondents by construction --
not a calibrated false-positive rate. Adjust the target tail with \code{fpr}, or
pass an absolute \code{cutoff} in \verb{[-1, 1]} to flag on a literal correlation
threshold. \code{fpr} and \code{cutoff} are mutually exclusive.

\strong{Abstention.} A respondent with fewer than three complete synonym pairs (an
all-missing row included), or whose answered pair values have zero variance (a
straightliner), has no defined correlation: both \code{value} and \code{flagged} are \code{NA}
and the row is excluded from the flag count and rate.
